[[File:N.hartland029.jpg|right|250px|thumb|North Hartland Dam]]
'''North Hartland Dam''' (National ID # VT00002) is a dam in [[Windsor County, Vermont]].

The earthen dam was constructed in 1961 by the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]], with a height of 182 feet, and a length of 1640 feet at its crest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ce-npdp-serv2.stanford.edu/DamDirectory/DamDetail.jsp?npdp_id=VT00002|title=Dam Name - North Hartland Dam 
|publisher=Ce-npdp-serv2.stanford.edu|accessdate=2012-09-24}}</ref> It impounds the [[Ottauquechee River]] for flood control and storm water management.  The dam is owned and operated by the New England District, [[North Atlantic Division]], U.S. Army Corps of Engineers.  

The riverine reservoir it creates, North Hartland Lake, has a normal water surface of 215 acres, a maximum capacity of 94,600 [[acre-feet]], and a much smaller normal capacity of 2350 acre-feet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://findlakes.com/northcentral_new_york_lakes_n44w75.htm |title=Piercefield Flow Lake Titus Lake Clear Area |publisher=Findlakes.com |date=2007-03-01 |accessdate=2012-09-24}}</ref>  Recreation includes fishing, swimming and boating in the summer, and winter sports such as snowmobiling, cross country skiing, and snowshoeing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nae.usace.army.mil/recreati/nhl/nhlrec.htm |title=North Hartland Lake, Vermont |publisher=Nae.usace.army.mil |date= |accessdate=2012-09-24}}</ref>

